column4: Awesome filming, great story thanks for making it and highlighting her story.

As someone who broke both bones on his right arm, and now rides with a few extra bolts and titanium plates, seeing that moment were you lie in bed very injured and still are just happy and focusing on being able to mimic the pedaling motion with your feet.... that really hits me. That single instant, I see you just grasping for a hope of freedom again - that must have taken a lot of courage. Very few of us watching this would pull that off, and all you did - including "scratching" off the race after all that. Which... by the way.. is the 2nd most courageous thing - recognizing that what you were no longer shows in the mirror. Thank you for sharing all of this with us. The tears, the pain, the crooked walking - this is what makes it real, and brave. It's not about winning races, or medals - it's always about taking the biggest punch in the face, and showing up again the next day.You kick ass.

Anna - your strength and perseverance is inspirational! I’m amazed at how well you’ve bounced back considering the extent of your crash. All that said, please consider treatment for the emotional scars that are clearly still present from your trauma… something specific to PTSI and that includes EMDR!

I feel conflicted. It’s a good attempt at a difficult subject. Not all stories are happy, or even necessarily inspiring, but I am not sure what to make of this ultimately.

A very good film put together by Rufus and Steve on behalf of Rapha. It is however (as someone else in the comments mentioned) deeply conflicting. On the one hand Ana's singleminded and stubborn pursuit of her goals is inspirational. On the other side of the coin, her selfishness has clearly come with considerable cost. Achieving a balance between both sides of the coin is to me what makes cycling so enjoyable. Watching this film I am not sure she is even close to achieving that balance. Am I inspired? For sure. Am I saddened for her? Absolutely.

Plain and simple, I believe in EQUALITY. Meaning if you want to be equal to your male counterparts than you should be doing 20 stages versus an abbreviated version of 10 stages. I blame the girls in that they should fight for equality. I blame UCI treating the girls as secondary. I blame the team. Looking at the meeting it is like secondary to the males. What kind of van is that? Have you seen the buses the guys have? What kind of director is that? He is an amateur! Can you not communicate or talk tactics with the girls? Watching this film is like watching Division III or the minor leagues versus their males in Division I or the major leagues. Remember Joan Benoit won the first womans marathon in the LA Olympics. That was a turning point for womans sports. If you want to do the same than you need to request the same distance, the same buses and the same equipment, the same tactics, the same everything.

I enjoyed watching this and so pleased the Tour is back and giving women's cycling a higher profile. This was more of a stylistic film than a documentary though  and at times confusing. In particular, it is not true that there hasn't been a women's Tour for 33 years. There have been various versions of the event from the 1990s through to 2013, and the fact that they may not have been organised by ASO should not diminish the achievements of the riders who won them. Nicole Cooke won the Grande Boucle Feminine in 2006 and 2007. She and riders such as Emma Pooley did a huge amount to raise the profile of women's cycling and campaign for more equal representation in the sport. I'd love to watch a film that documents the history accurately.

I discovered this series through forced time off the bike, but was able to slowly claw my way back into full training. Am now fully back to shredding centuries with efforts and beating records on climbs in Switzerland. You guys were a huge support throughout the year. Keep up the great work :) THANK YOU SO MUCH!! 🙏🙏🙏❤‍🩹

I'm going to provide a counterpoint to all of the lavish praise in the comments. One reason cycling is dying is that there are not enough aspirational figures in the sport. An "aw shucks," self-deprecating dorkiness permeates the culture. The men at the forefront of the sport do not exactly embody the hard-nosed, badass masculinity like an Armstrong did, or to compare to other sports, a Lebron or Ronaldo or Tom Brady. These cyclists would get eaten by those other sportsmen. And for better or worse, LA back in the day wouldn't... his vibe was totally different, and an entire generation was attracted to that. Alex and Lachlan are super chill, likeable guys. But kids watching this are not going to leave thinking "wow, cycling is super badass!" like they feel after watching a Nike commercial about myriad other sports. It's too bad because cycling is a pretty badass sport.

It's a great atmosphere. I did this several times back in the 90s before it got trendy. Did the Vail Ultra 100 too when it started up a rivalry with Leadville. They'd be one week after the other. Vail is too polished for me. Didn't like staying there.I lived in California at the time, so trained a lot at high altitude in the Sierras, so I would arrive acclimatized, so it wasn't too bad. I did the race in 2000 after living in the UK for a while, and suffered badly. Had to visit the medical tent afterwards and breathe oxygen. And for the rest of the week, couldn't sleep properly because of being unable to catch a full breath.They are right about "The Powerline". It's not a road. It's just where power pylons go STRAIGHT up the mountain, so it's a 20% gradient dirt trail.The trail up to Columbine mine is not too bad for most of its length. Above the tree line it's only semi rideable upwards.

Arguably one of the most noteworthy performances here is hardly featured at all since the rider, Quinn Simmons  (finishing  @20:05),  was not one of the "chosen” few for this video.  In fact he isn’t even mentioned by name despite finishing on the podium. Full story here: https://durangoherald.com/articles/289241 Short version: He rode with the leaders, lost contact (and much time) due to punctures from tacks on the course, chased back riding solo to take the sprint for second. An epic effort and result. And he was a junior! He also had another pretty good result on the road the following month: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hRAWul6Nd4IFun fact- the last American to win the junior world road championships was a fellow named Greg LeMond.

I have some advice for Leadville100 in 2020...........Have the downtown area roped off at the corner turn & supervised by police to keep lots of  cheaters from cutting in at the last minute after the start.  I personally watch this happen in 2019.  Not fair to cyclist who are in their correct corrals early before the start.  It matters when seconds count at the 40 mile marker before your sweepers disappoint riders who trained hard to get to that important marker by 10:30.  My son completed all his pre-course races in alotted time, so he could be disappointed at 40 mile marker by less than 1 minute during Leadville100. (His computer chip time was under 10:30) , yet his number was pulled.  There are TOO many riders bunched up trying to get into a rhythm the first 20 miles, which slows all cyclists down.   CHEATERS should be stopped.  Lots of money and time is invested in this race & I expect a professional race committee to oversee it.  You call yourself one of the best,  I say demonstrate it , instead of just talking about it.  YOU need to DIG DEEP and show all riders you really care.  MAJOR  MONEY is fed into your economy during the race series.  SIGNED by a MOM & 9th year CENTURY RIDER FROM TEXAS where temps are 108-113 at finish line.

Some pro road teams have money and win races. EF might win fewer races, but they have something extra - passion - the rare kind of passion that inspires everyday cyclists across all disciplines and can't be bought. Someone sent me this when I was at a very low ebb I have terminal rare appendix cancer and I am mostly alone to deal with it.  Before my diagnosis I was cycling and hiking, love the outdoors and nature, love camping and just being.  Today I struggle to see sense in it all, my pain is increasing and I am unable to cycle or walk far and feel my life is over but now I have to suffer the pain to reach that end.  After reaching out on Facebook someone sent me this video, from this day forth I will watch this every day and I know it’ll change my mindset. My cancer is incurable and now it’s a waiting game but I’m determined that my last breath will be taken doing what I love, cycling, walking and being with nature.  This video is my inspiration until my final breath Thank you for this great video and the truest words I’ve heard in a long time. Hope is all I have left.

I was given six months to live at 37 with multiple myeloma.  I had breast cancer at 30. Two bone-marrow transplants, years of chemo.   Mountain biking saved my life.... I was diagnosed with testicular cancer in 1993. I had radiotherapy only, so I think I was very lucky. I remember seeing the puir souls who were receiving chemo!at the Glasgow hospital I attended, sitting in their chairs with the ubiquitous drips attached to their arms.Cancer takes away choice (as Justin says), and to a certain extent dignity. Watching this man’s determination to tell cancer that he would make definitive choices every day is both humbling and inspirational. Lang may yer lum reek, Justin.

THE ONLY PART CONFUSING in this video is the girl saying that some days she hates her bike. I ride a lot too, but I don't recall a day I hate my bike. I recall a moment I hated my bike, it was 120 miles into a 9k feet climbing day, at hour 7:00:00, I started to wonder why I was putting myself through it... then 2 days later (and after taking one day off) I was in the best shape of my life. 2 months later I was winning a race (even though I am usually one of the fast guys around, I am not much of a racer. I cant stand the dumb dudes throwing their bikes on you). I am not of a Rapha kind of rider. I like to ride for the love and pleasure of it. I like to see things, I don't mind taking pulls to pull the lazy guys that never want to pull, they like to save it for that final popular stretch, but still, even after pulling them to the sprint, I will still beat all of them if not most of them... Cycling has changed my life and health, for better

Despite continued asking over the decades, so-called 'Icelandic Dick' Phillips claimed all the photos and  rock samples collected on the 1958 trip were "lost in the post". They only emerged once photographer Raymond Bottomley dies and Bernard Heath in a care home, 60 years later. Where did Ron acquire the slides and photos taken by, but denied to Raymond Bottomley...

There is a folder containing letters, newspaper clippings, accounts of supplies etc for the organising of this trip. This was before Ron was involved. It is such a shame that this video was not made when Raymond Bottomley and Bernard Heath were still alive.

Wow this is COOL. It's my 47th Birthday and I bought myself a Trek Checkpoint to explore on, to cover the gaps in the bike collection. I sat down with my morning tea only to see this great video. I have been into bikes since being about 5 years old, and when I was around 14-15 my late father surprised me and gave me the best present ever, he took me to Paris from London City Airport to watch the end of the tour, this was an incredible experience and one of my fondest memories, and to top it off, we met Andy after the finish! He was sat on a car bonnet surrounded by people and he smiled through the sweat and exhaustion and signed an autograph for me! Somewhere I have a photograph.So this video today, on my birthday, felt like another present from Dad, to encourage me to keep riding. Thanks Rapha, and thanks Andy!

Beautiful film of a beautiful bicycle ride.  I've done this 600km, 2-day, ride a few times, although never in snow.  Strong winds, horizontal sleet, biblical downpours and even warm sunshine (all in the space of a couple of hours and in sight of Snowdon) but never snow like that.  The Rapha boys back up their products by riding with us "normals" on some epic rides.  Yes their clothes are expensive but I've never yet sent any back and I'm willing to save up until I can afford more.  The only people I know who criticise their gear are people who never owned any.

3:35 Simon Cowell?

Dear Connie & Davis, as I get older, you were & continue to be an inspiration.  When you were young racing the Coors classic & the 84 Olympics I was working for the Japan Group (ie Shimano, Tioga, etc etc), and I was a Cat-1 having the time of my life.  Just like you, that's when I met the girl of my life Connie Shim (Korean), who was the secretary for Shimano USA Ken Fujimura. Both she and I were sent to San Fransisco to attend the Coors Classic start and when we saw each other, it was love at first sight.  We were happily married 24 years.  My wife and I eventually went on to found onZa.   Its so nice to see you guys and hopefully holding together.  Sincerely Dan

Thanks Rapha. I will ride again. Starting tomorrow . Tonight I will charge my tail lights, and both of my headlights. I will air up my tires to a comfortable 100 psi. The Gaidhealtachd is one of the most beautiful and brutal areas of the World. I am Scottish, and have a bit of the Gaidhlig, and that part of Scotland is steeped in sadness, as much as beauty. If you go, take some time to understand the Gaels' history, as well as fretting over whether your gear ratios are good for the terrain. When I cycle there, it's like meditation.

To be honest, as a Filipino, I find this video... problematic.I commend those behind this video for having exposed the coded racism they encountered while cycling through the American heartland during Donald Trump's fascist reign. They could have just edited that out to create a feel-good video.But then again, the locals they encountered wouldn't have confided with those xenophobic and racist coded comments if the cyclists weren't white.The cyclists refrained from commenting when the locals spoke with xenophobic and racist coded comments and avoided confrontation. This is understandable, with them just passing through. But also perhaps they were neutral and ambivalent. With their silence, we are left wondering, suspecting. One thing is clear, a person of color such as I would not have that same luxury or privilege of being confided to or keeping silent about it.As a Filipino, I can't help but wonder, would those same xenophobes and racists be as honest or as welcoming if the cyclists were people of color such as I? Would they pretend to be nice or be openly hostile to cyclists and a camera crew with people of color?Is it too much to ask for people to counter racism and xenophobia whenever it rears its ugly head, however inconvenient? Is silence consent?What would I do if I myself was confronted with the same racism and xenophobia, however coded and oblique, on my cycling adventures abroad?

I really enjoyed this!!! What a great adventure along a truly iconic route. The cinematography was outstanding. Kudos to everyone in creating this extraordinary journey. I particularly liked the fact that all the cyclists were not completely "rapha'd" out! Of course, it is a Rapha production, and surely wearing some Rapha kit is a given. However, the mixing and matching between Pieces in the Rapha collection and "ordinary or civilian" wear was refreshing and welcoming to see. It made the characters and the overall vibe of the film more enjoyable and approachable. More real and, therefore,  potentially more inspiring for a wide range of cyclists. It is an ethos that Sami was talking about towards the end of the film- where it's about riding and wearing what you have....Just ride! I think sometimes people see cyclists or encouner other cyclists in the road and get snubbed because a person is not kitted up to the nines, particularly, in a kit that is so name recognized like Rapha. For sure, there is a time and a place to wear performance enhancing kit and, Rapha is not to blame for the snobbery of certain cyclists and their misunderstanding if what it is to just go for a spin. That is why the apparel choices of the riders was so cool and possibly eye-opening to a larger audience that the kit doesn't make the rider, the ride or experience makes it! Job well done! #everyrideisepic

Stop it with the Helmet-Shaming. There is no law in the US that you have to wear a helmet on Route 66.  Nobody is anti-safety, but as it should be, it is a personal choice to wear, or not want to wear, a helmet, or a chest protector, or kneepads, elbow pads, wrist guards, padded lycra, safety glasses, high-visibility neon clothing, etc. If you want to put on armour and look like a Power Ranger every time you ride, so be it. Not everyone else wants to do that for every ride, particularly if they are filming and they don't want competing logos everywhere. Nor do they have to "set an example" for your kids, that's your job. Stop chastising others for not riding how you ride.

Disgusto total con Rapha:Realizo un pedido a Rapha, una chaqueta de invierno con cortavientos. Siguiendo sus recomendaciones de talla, pues tuve que devolver un pedido anterior por quedarme pequeño. Había pedido un par de maillots core XL, por cierto nada de otro mundo, por no decir algo peor la línea core, y me dicen que ahora pida la XXL, me parece una burrada, pero bueno.Llega la chaqueta, talla enorme en comparación a lo anterior y me queda grande. Pero la chaqueta además venía con un cordón de ajuste suelto.Hasta aquí todo perfecto, les devuelvo la chaqueta, por supuesto sin usar ni nada parecido, peeeero me contestan a los pocos días que me envían la chaqueta de nuevo porque la he roto y no está en condiciones de venta. (El cordón de ajuste que ya me venía suelto).Les respondo al correo que me envían, les envio correos, explicándoles el tema y nada...Muy bien, hasta ahora llevo comprados 3 culotes, chaleco, ropa de mi mujer, y alguna cosilla más...Esta ha sido mi última compra y por supuesto, no puedo hacer nada buena publicidad de su atención al cliente.Pero lo peor del caso:¿Tan mala presuponen sú propia ropa que sin haberse estrenado pueden soltarse/descoserse los cordones de ajuste?Mal vamos entonces.Esta vez un Cero, Rapha.

As a German living in Taiwan for nearly 30 years I would like to give some comments to this video.“Taipei is not a huge city!” Taipei has an estimated 2,700,000 (!)  Citizens, from one side of the city to the other side I need at least ½ by bike one way. I live on the other side of Taipei in Xindian, would spend at least one hour (one way) to ride to the foot of Yangmingshan, later mentioned in the same video. This is a huge city for bike riders!       “Riverside Cycling Path” was a great addition but on weekends for sports riders due to very high frequency of families, children, elderly and inexperienced riders on bikes next to useless until you want to practice your breaking and balance skills. “You can escape the traffic by climbing hilly roads of the suburbs” is a nice comment but the video is titled ‘Rapha Rides Taipei’ (City). There is a difference between Taipei City and New Taipei City, the latter is the 'suburbs of Taipei City'.“The traffic is often congested by scooters and vehicles” is only part of the problem. The more serious problem is the Diesel-old oil mixture which they call Eco-Diesel and is burned and blown uncleaned into the atmosphere by buses and trucks. Ever noticed the black smoke when buses and trucks start from a standstill? These are the Diesel-recycled oil particles you inhale riding bike in Taipei City! The other point is the lack of respect for bicycle riders from all other parties (trucks, cars, scooters and even pedestrians) and the lack of obeying traffic rules from fellow bike riders using clearly seen clipless pedals. One visual example @1:18. Once I had to remind a Dad running a red traffic light that he is teaching his son, a Junior High School student, to run red lights from a very young age by following this father!“The roads of Yangmingshan” are not in the Taipei City but on the outskirts. The car numbers are restricted and the restriction is enforced, that’s why the hills near Yangmingshan are great for cycling. I live on the other side of Taipei in Xindian and would spend at least one hour (one way) just to reach the Yangmingshan area.“The traffic, while busy, has its own unwritten laws that keep it smoothly” I get permanently cut, blocked by turning cars on the road or cars leaving gas stations, get passed in dangerous close distance and shaken up by horns of egoistic truck drivers. I suppose, these are the ‘unwritten laws.’  One visual example @ 1:12.“I know that Taipei has plenty of room for improvement compared to other cities” is hopefully a good start in the right direction.Don’t get me wrong, I rode since the beginning of May until today (mid of November) 3.700 km on Taiwan roads happily but only ride in or to Taipei City for buying parts for my bike. And every time I am happy to leave…
